<DOC><DOCNO> AP890726-0207 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 2153EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-SpaceJob     07-26 0167</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Space Job,150</SECOND><HEAD>Aaron Cohen Of Johnson Space Center Named To Moon-Mars Study Job</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Aaron Cohen, director of the Johnson SpaceCenter in Houston, will lead the participation by the NationalAeronautics and Space Administration in a study of the nationalgoal of exploring the moon and the planet Mars, the space agencyannounced Wednesday.   Richard H. Truly, NASA administrator, said Cohen will beassigned temporarily to NASA headquarters for the next few months.   Truly said the assignment is in response to President Bush'sspeech last Thursday on the 20th anniversary of the Apollo 11 moonlanding. In that speech, Bush asked the National Space Council todetermine what is needed to establish an outpost on the moon andlater to conduct a manned exploration of Mars.   Cohen will be direct NASA's participation in preparing thoserecommendations, Truly said.   While Cohen is assigned to Washington, Truly said deputydirector Paul Weitz, a former astronaut, will be in charge of theJohnson Space Center.</TEXT></DOC>